  "prompt": "Is it correct to use the phrase \"revert back\" in a sentence? I hear it all the time and on occasion even on BBC!",
  "response": "The phrase \"revert back\" is commonly used in conversation, but it is considered redundant because \"revert\" already implies going back to a previous state. The word \"back\" is unnecessary. It would be more concise to simply say \"revert.\" \n\nFor example, instead of saying \"Please revert back to me on this matter,\" you could say \"Please revert to me on this matter.\" However, because \"revert back\" is widely used, many people understand it in context, even if it is not technically correct.",
